                      lifespan of 10-15 years. If the stove is nearing or has
                      surpassed this range, replacement might be more
                      cost-effective.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Overall Condition: Check for wear and tear, rust, and
                      other signs of deterioration. A stove in generally poor
                      condition may be better replaced.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Evaluate Repair Costs vs. Replacement Costs</b>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Repair Costs: Get an estimate for the repair. If the
                      repair cost is more than half the cost of a new stove,
                      replacement is often the better option.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Replacement Costs: Consider not just the purchase price
                      but also installation costs and potential downtime.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Consider Efficiency and Performance</b>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Energy Efficiency: Newer models are typically more energy
                      efficient, which can result in significant savings over
                      time.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Performance: If the stove is not performing adequately
                      (e.g., uneven cooking, frequent breakdowns), it might be
                      hindering your kitchenâ€™s productivity.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Frequency of Breakdowns</b>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Repair History: If the stove has required multiple repairs
                      in the recent past, it may be more economical to replace
                      it.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Downtime Impact: Frequent breakdowns can disrupt
                      operations and affect customer satisfaction.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Availability of Parts</b>
                  <ul>
                    <p>
                      Parts Availability: For older models, parts may be hard to
                      find or very expensive. If parts are no longer available
                      or are prohibitively expensive, replacement is likely
                      necessary.
                    </p>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Safety Concerns</b>
                  <ul>
                    <p>
                      Safety Issues: Any safety concerns, such as gas leaks or
                      electrical problems, should be addressed immediately.
                      Sometimes, replacement is the safest option.
                    </p>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Compliance with Regulations</b>
                  <ul>
                    <p>
                      Regulatory Compliance: Ensure the stove meets current
                      health and safety regulations. Older models might not
                      comply with new standards.
                    </p>
                  </ul>
                </li>
